Figure 1.

Abundance of Lobster from 2012-2017: AQUE stays relatively consistent CARP starts increasing after 2015, with a big spike between 2016 and 2017 IVEE increases from 2012 to 2015, decreases from 2015 and 2016, and increases again to 2017 MOHK spikes between 2014 and 2015, then steadily decreases to 2017 NAPL increases steadily between 2012 and 2015, then decreases steadily to 2017 IVEE, MOHK, and NAPL all increase in abundance between 2013 and 2015, but then all decrease to 2016. Out of these 3 sites, only IVEE rapidly increases in abundance from 2016 to 2017; the other 2 sites (MOHK & NAPL) decrease slightly. CARP and AQUE both don’t have large changes in abundance from 2012 to 2015; after 2015, AQUE abundance decreases a little, and CARP increases, with a large increase from 2016 to 2017.

# Problem 4. Proportions of “legal” lobsters at the 5 sites in 2017. The legal minimum carapace size for lobster is 82.6 mm. What proportion of observed lobsters at each site are above the legal minimum? Does that proportion differ significantly across the 5 sites? Note: We’ll be doing chi-square in labs next week, or go ahead with maximum resourcefulness and check out the chisq.test() function on your own!

# Make a contingency table for lobster carapace size:
lob_size <- lob_abun_simple %>% # Create data frame for lobster carapace size from "lob_abun_simple" data frame (created in Problem 2), which has data in tidy format
  filter(YEAR == 2017) %>% 
  mutate(Legality = ifelse(SIZE < 82.6, "ILLEGAL", "LEGAL")) %>% 
  select(SITE, Legality) %>% 
  count(SITE, Legality) %>% 
  spread(Legality, n) %>% 
  select(-SITE)
  
rownames(lob_size) <- c("AQUE", "CARP", "IVEE", "MOHK", "NAPL")
## Warning: Setting row names on a tibble is deprecated.
lob_size
## # A tibble: 5 x 2
##   ILLEGAL LEGAL
## *   <int> <int>
## 1      51    16
## 2     526   179
## 3     476   130
## 4     154    24
## 5      75    37
lob_prop <- prop.table(as.matrix(lob_size), 1) # Look at the actual proportions
lob_prop
##        ILLEGAL     LEGAL
## AQUE 0.7611940 0.2388060
## CARP 0.7460993 0.2539007
## IVEE 0.7854785 0.2145215
## MOHK 0.8651685 0.1348315
## NAPL 0.6696429 0.3303571
# Perform chi-square test for independence on the count data (not proportions)
lob_x2 <- chisq.test(lob_size)
lob_x2
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  lob_size
## X-squared = 18.497, df = 4, p-value = 0.0009864
lob_x2$stdres # If beyond 2, pay attention for significance...
##         ILLEGAL      LEGAL
## AQUE -0.1464223  0.1464223
## CARP -1.8631463  1.8631463
## IVEE  1.2357993 -1.2357993
## MOHK  3.2327773 -3.2327773
## NAPL -2.5706474  2.5706474
# There IS a significant association between legal lobster size between the 5 sites! Look at 'Values' section to see what things you can call from the output.

# create kable table of proportion of legal lobsters at each site
lob_table <- kable(lob_prop) %>%
